[1
Date: Fri, 24 Sep 1999 21:59:54 -0300
From: ProMED <promed@usa.healthnet.org>

Source: Media Release from CDC, (404) 639-3286
See CDC's web page, 24 Sep 1999
<http://www.cdc.gov/od/oc/media/pressrel/r990924.htm>

CDC, in collaboration with the New York City and New York State departments
of health, has isolated and identified a West Nile-like virus from birds
that died in New York City and were submitted for testing by the Bronx Zoo.
West Nile virus is an arbovirus closely related to St. Louis encephalitis
virus, but generally causes a milder disease in humans. Both viruses are
transmitted through the bite of a mosquito that becomes infected with the
virus by feeding on an infected bird. Like St. Louis encephalitis, West
Nile virus is not transmitted from person to person or from birds to
persons. West Nile virus never before has been recognized in the United
States or any other area of the Western Hemisphere.
Since late August, New York City has been experiencing an outbreak of
arboviral (mosquito-borne) encephalitis. Previously, diagnostic tests on
serum from human cases in this outbreak were reported as consistent with
St. Louis encephalitis virus infection. At present, the relationship
between this isolation of West Nile-like virus from birds in New York City
and the outbreak of encephalitis among persons in New York City remains
uncertain and further laboratory testing is underway. The CDC is testing
these and additional human specimens for the possibility of West Nile-like
virus infection.
CDC and city and state health departments emphasize that current mosquito
control efforts by individuals and communities are appropriate because the
same mosquito species transmit both viruses. Individuals should continue
to do the following to reduce their contact with mosquitoes:
When outdoors, wear clothing that covers the skin such as long sleeve
shirts and pants; spray clothing and exposed skin with insect repellant.
Curb outside activity at dawn, dusk and during the evening.
Communities should continue to do the following:
Raise public awareness about the outbreak, control measures, and personal
protection.
Continue current efforts of mosquito control. CDC further recommends that
communities in the area should consider mosquito spraying if they have not
yet done so.
*****
[2
The New York Times also has an article on this topic:
"African Virus May Be Culprit in Mosquito-Borne Illnesses in New York Region"
<http://www.nytimes.com/library/national/regional/092599ny-encephalitis.html>
http://www.nytimes.com/library/nationa
l/regional/092599ny-encephalitis.html/regional/092599ny-encephalitis.html>

In part, it says that West Nile virus [WNV was discovered this week in
dozens of birds that died in and around the Bronx Zoo this summer. Blood
samples from people with symptoms, trapped mosquitoes, as well as roughly
450 birds will be examined by the CDC. to see whether the WNV virus found
in the birds was what has caused the New Yorkers to become ill.
The discovery of WNV came about in large part by determined investigations
by Tracy McNamara, head of the department of pathology at the Bronx Zoo,
Federal officials said. In late July Dr. McNamara became concerned when
she heard that a large number of crows had been dying around the zoo. By
August, 40 crows had died. Then, birds at the zoo began to die.
Over Labor Day weekend, the zoo lost a Guanay Cormorant, three Chilean
flamingos, a pheasant and a bald eagle. Because these deaths followed those
of the crows, experts strongly doubt that the disease originated in the
zoo.
Autopsies of the birds revealed streaking in the heart and brain
hemorrhages. Eastern equine encephalitis was suspected, but McNamara was
skeptical, because the emus in her care, which are very susceptible to
eastern equine encephalitis virus, were thriving.
When two more flamingos died on Sept. 9, she sent samples to laboratories
of the United States Department of Agriculture, in Ames, Iowa, which ruled
out all the common bird viruses. "It was becoming more and more suggestive
that this was not a regular bird disease," McNamara said. The CDC was also
sent samples, as were doctors at an Army lab in Fort Detrick in Maryland.
Yesterday, the CDC discovered the WNV link. "Everyone was shocked," she
said. "It's possible it came in with a human or a smuggled bird, and I am
not at all certain it will ever be established how it got here."
The Mayor's Office of Emergency Management, which has been in charge of the
spraying, would not comment on the CDC news.
