[This is one of the most remarkable occurrences I have seen in 35 years
working with arthropod-borne viruses. This strain of WNV might have
entered the U.S. in an infected bird or an infected human, either of whom
might have been viremic for the length of time it takes a jet plane to
travel from essentially throughout Africa, where it is enzootic, or from
Europe, where this virus has appeared recently with greater frequency and
apparent pathogenicity (vide supra, archived messages re: Romania, and
Italy). A recent issue of Emerging Infectious Diseases
<http://www.cdc.gov> contains a report on human WNV infections in the Czech
Republic; older literature reports mention the virus in Europe from
Portugal, Croatia, Cyprus, and the former Soviet Union.
If WNV has entered the U.S. in exotic, imported birds, it should be
relatively easy to check the Bronx Zoo's recent import records and dates of
death of any of those birds. It will also be necessary to check records of
arrivals of exotic birds at NY City and area bird dealers. The U.S.
Department of Agriculture (Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service =
APHIS) should also have import records.
Irrespective of the method by which WNV has entered the U.S., this is a
stunning discovery. Keep in mind that to this moment it has not been shown
that any of the human infections, with what has been reported as St. Louis
encephalitis (SLE) virus, have actually been WNV infections. Therefore,
this may be the oddest of coincidences but, as C.J. Peters has said, "When
you hear hoof beats, think horses, not zebras". That may hold for the U.S.
but not for Africa. Still, such a coincidence would be remarkable. There
had been no reports of the presence of SLE virus anywhere in the eastern
U.S., except in the NY City area; ProMED had mused on the source of the
index SLEV-infected bird. As we reported on 22 September [St. Louis
enceph. - USA(New York, Westchester County) 990922002538, not only was
"SLE virus" detected in mosquitoes collected on a Greenwich, Connecticut,
golf course but the virus also was isolated from the brain of a dead crow
removed from a home in Westport, Connecticut, the same species dying near
the Bronx Zoo.
WNV has been isolated from humans, birds, camels, bats, rodents, horses,
ticks, and many species of mosquitoes. However, these isolations have all
been from places outside the U.S., so it is not clear how the CDC and local
health departments can say that "current mosquito control efforts by
individuals and communities are appropriate because the same mosquito
species transmit both viruses".
If the crows and other birds began dying in July, why did the first human
cases of whatever this is not begin to appear until late August, in Queens
County?
St. Louis encephalitis virus and West Nile virus are both members of the
West Nile antigenic complex of the virus family Flaviviridae. They are
very closely related viruses and might be confused. However, arbovirus
identification can be tricky business. One usually "screens" an isolate
against a battery of antibodies to viruses suspected to occur in an area
(there are more than 500 recognized arboviruses). After detecting reaction
with antibody to one or more viruses, confirmatory neutralization tests are
done. Nucleotide sequencing follows, so that the molecular epidemiology of
the virus and the possible source and route of movement can be ascertained.
Obviously, this has not yet been done with the SLE virus isolates. Until
adequate and appropriate neutralization tests are conducted the
identification can only be called provisional.
Vincent Deubel, Pasteur Institute, Paris, has considerable experience with
the molecular epidemiology of WNV and will likely be called in to consult
on further studies.
Seems to me that Dr. Tracy McNamara deserves considerable praise for her
keen observances. - Mod.CHC
...................jw/chc/es
